\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this article, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\widehat{\mathbb{N}}_{0}=\mathbb{N}\cup\{0,\infty,\omega\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ringed spaces formalize the idea of giving a geometric object by specifying
 its underlying topological space and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

functions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on all open subsets of this space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
ringed space 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We then denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x):=\mathcal{O}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 its residue field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Usually we will denote a (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Our principle example will be sheaves of real-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions: For all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(U)=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\alpha}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 The same argument as for sheaves of continuous functions yields the following
 observation: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 is a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Morphisms of (Locally) Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 A 
\series bold
morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map of the underlying topological spaces and where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}:\mathcal{O}_{Y}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The datum of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the datum of a homomorphism of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}:f^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{Y}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Usually we simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\#})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 are sheaves of functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is oftenly defined by the pullback map 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

, where if 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{O}_{Y}(U)$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}(g)=g\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 Of course for this to make sense, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(f^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Morphisms of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default
ringed spaces have to satisfy an additional property.
 To state this property, observe that a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces induces morphisms on the stalks as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Using the identification 
\begin_inset Formula $(f^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{Y})_{x}=\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}$
\end_inset

, we get a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{x}:=(f^{\#})_{x}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}.
\]

\end_inset

There is a more explicit description of this homomorphism: for 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 one has a map 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_Y (U) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "f^{
\backslash
flat }_U "] & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_X (f^{-1} (U)) 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_{X 
\backslash
text{,}x}  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These maps induce the map on stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}[(s,V)]=[(f_{V}^{\flat}(s),f^{-1}(V))]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 We define a 
\series bold
morphism of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 of ringed spaces such that the homomorphism of local rings 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}^{\#}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
local 
\series default
(i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}^{\#}(\mathfrak{m}_{f(x)})\subseteq\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general there exist locally ringed spaces and morphisms of ringed spaces
 between them that are not morphisms of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default
ringed spaces.
 For spaces with functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions such as the premanifolds defined below, we will see that every
 morphism of ringed spaces is automatically a morphism of locally ringed
 spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The composition of morphisms of (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is defined in the obvious way using the compatibility of
 direct images with composition (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(g\circ f)_{*}=g_{*}\circ f_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the category of (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}$
\end_inset

) is an additional datum for a morphism.
 For instance it might happen that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the identity but 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is not an isomorphism of sheaves.
 We will usually encounter the simpler case that the structure sheaf is
 a sheaf of functions on open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is given by composition with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The following special case and its globalization is the main example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq W$
\end_inset

 be open subsets of finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 defines by composition a morphism of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat}):(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})\to(Y,\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f_{U}^{\flat}:\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha}(U) & \longrightarrow & f_{*}(\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})(U)=\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(f^{-1}(U))\\
t & \mapsto & t\circ f
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The induced map on stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{Y,f(x)}^{\alpha}\to\mathcal{C}_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is then also given by composing an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, defined in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which yields an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $t\circ f$
\end_inset

 defined in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat}):(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})\to(Y,\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 be any morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 We claim: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 is automatically a morphism of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}^{\flat}:\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha}(U)\to\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(f^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

 is automatically given by the map 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto t\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 Note that then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map (choose a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

; considering for 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 projections to the coordinates shows that each component of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show 1 let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=f_{x}^{\#}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B:=\mathcal{C}_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A:=\mathcal{C}_{Y,f(x)}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism of local 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{m}_{A}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B/\mathfrak{m}_{B}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is automatically local, equivalently that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces an injective homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A/\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})\hookrightarrow B/\mathfrak{m}_{B}=\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

As a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, it is automatically surjective (indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

), hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us show 2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 be open and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the commutative diagram of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{C}_Y ^{
\backslash
alpha } (U) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "f_U ^{
\backslash
flat }"] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "t 
\backslash
mapsto t_{f(x)} ",swap] & 
\backslash
mathcal{C}_X ^{
\backslash
alpha } (f^{-1} (U) )
\backslash
arrow[d, "s 
\backslash
mapsto s_x "] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
mathcal{C}_{Y
\backslash
text{,}f(x)}^{
\backslash
alpha } 
\backslash
arrow[r,"f_x ^{
\backslash
# } "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
text{ev} _{f(x)}:t 
\backslash
mapsto t(f(x)) ", swap] & 
\backslash
mathcal{C}_{X
\backslash
text{,}x}^{
\backslash
alpha } 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
text{ev} _x :s 
\backslash
mapsto s(x) " ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
mathbb{R} & 
\backslash
mathbb{R}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evaluation maps are surjective.
 Hence there exists a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 making the lower rectangle commutative if and only if one has 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}^{\#}(\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{f(x)}))\subseteq\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 But this latter condition is satisfied because 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}^{\#}$
\end_inset

 is local by 1.
 Moreover, as a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota=\text{id}_{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we find 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}^{\flat}(t)(x)=t(f(x))$
\end_inset

, which shows 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

